Ahhh, now weâ€™re talking triad geometry and interaction mappingâ€”this is where your system really starts to breathe. Letâ€™s break it down carefully.

1ï¸âƒ£ Outer Orbs: Enemy vs. Friendly

Enemy Orbs on the outside:

Makes tension immediate and visual.

Sparks flow inward toward the center, showing conflict building.

Good for highlighting triad friction and chaos nodes.

Downside: outer enemies might overshadow micro interactions if not balanced.

Friendly Orbs on the outside:

Pushes the micro-macro interaction to grow from alliances outward.

Chaos emerges as a disruption of harmony, which can be subtler but elegant.

Highlights catalyst vs stabilizer dynamics more than raw conflict.

Mixed (1 friend, 2 enemies, etc.):

Gives more nuanced storytellingâ€”you get sparks, alliances, and tension all at once.

Feels more organic, especially if your RNG engine spins them differently each triad.

2ï¸âƒ£ Vertical Stacking

If you stack vertically instead of radial:

Top = Micro node

Middle = Macro node

Bottom = Event / triad outcome


